<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the UK Minerals Forum (UKMF)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt">EIS 02</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the UK Minerals Forum (UKMF)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary:</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The UK Minerals Forum (UKMF), established in 2007 and funded by the CBI Minerals Group, brings together representatives of the UK’s onshore extractiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e industries, NGOs with a particular interest in the environmental impacts of mineral extraction, the sector’s research organisation, local government planners and observers from central government, the territorial administrations and the main statutory re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">gulators.  It aims to discuss matters of common interest in a neutral forum, away from the pressures of traditional lobbying, campaigning, and formal dialogue with government and its agencies over regulatory policy, legislation, minerals supply and environ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">mental protection.  The Forum sponsors Working Groups to look in more detail at matters of particular concern. These report back not only to UKMF itself but also to the wider public through suitable websites and the biennial CBI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Living with Minerals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Confer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ences.  They are followed up with government as appropriate.  Accordingly, UKMF offers itself as an example of Best Practice in extractive industry-NGO engagement.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This submission responds to the following question in the BIS Committee’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Call </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">for Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The United Kingdom Minerals Forum (UKMF) is off</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ered as an example of good practice in national-level strategic engagement between the onshore extractive industries and NGOs, local authority planners, other statutory regulators and central government, which the Committee might wish to note in considerin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g this question.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMF was launched in November 2006 at the CBI’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Living with Minerals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Conference by baroness Andrews, then Parliamentary Under Secretary at the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG).  This followed several years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of tentative discussion between the NGOs primarily interested in the impacts of onshore mineral extraction in the UK, the main minerals interests (principally in the aggregates sector responsible for the largest tonnages and numbers of extraction sites, b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ut acting under the broader umbrella of the CBI Minerals Group – CBIMG), and officials in the former Minerals and Waste Planning Division in DCLG.  There was a shared feeling that there would be mutual benefit from having a neutral forum, in which issues o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f common interest could be discussed and examined in more depth, separately from the usual round of formal discussions on UK and EU legislation, planning policy development and the management of minerals supply, which can at times become contentious.  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Forum began work in May 2007.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Membership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMF comprises the following interests</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Industry: via the CBIMG and its associated trade organisations – covering sectors producing coal, a range of construction and industrial materials including aggregates, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cement, silica sand, kaolin (china clay), ball clay, heavy (ceramic) clays, gypsum, salt and potash; (and, via CBIMG members, links to the Institute of Materials, Minerals and Mining, where the Forum normally meets).</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">NGOs – CPRE, RSPB and an independent en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vironmental consultant;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 67.02pt; padding-left:4.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local government; via the Minerals and Waste Group of the Planning Officers Society;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British Geological Survey (Minerals and Waste);</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 67.76pt; padding-left:4.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Mineral Industry Research Organisation;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 65.69pt; padding-left:6.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Statutory regulators (as observers): the Environmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t Agency, Natural England and English Heritage;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Central and UK territorial Government (as observers): with representatives from DCLG, Defra, BIS, the Scottish and Welsh Governments and the Northern Ireland Assembly.</span></li></ol><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 32.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Business model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Meetings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMF normally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> holds 3 plenary meetings a year in London, usually at the offices of the Institute of Materials, Minerals and Mining at 1 Carlton House Terrace, in March, June and November.  Its 21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> meeting was held in June 2013. Agendas cover matters of current interes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t, including regulatory policy, practice and legislation, and strategic issues on future minerals supply and their interaction with environmental considerations.  Topics over the period since June 2012 have included:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Future Working Groups topics and progra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mme;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Follow-up to earlier Working Group reports;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Regular policy and legislative updates from DCLG;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Regular round-ups of environmental news and issues collated by English Heritage for the NGOs and NDPBs represented on the Forum;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Strategic issues in policy and regulation – the National Planning Policy Framework, the review of the Habitats Regulations, the Resource Security Action Plan, the Red Tape Challenge, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">perspectives on the “Environmental Debate” </span></li></ol><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Working Groups</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMF also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sponsors and steers Working Groups examining topics in more depth.  These prepare reports which are discussed in the Forum and followed up as necessary usually with the relevant government departments.  They are also presented to the CBIMG’s biennial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Livi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ng with Minerals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Conferences.  Since 2007 the following topics have been examined:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 108pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2007-2008:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Declining mineral reserves and the futu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re security of supply; Mineral E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xtraction in the Nation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">al Parks and AONBs;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Carbon and Proximity in minerals supply; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cumulat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ive I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mpacts in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> policy, l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egislation and regulation.  (Reported to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Living with Minerals 3 in November 2008</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">);</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 108pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2010-2011:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Distributing minerals to future markets; Planning Skills [training specialist mineral planners], Communities and communication. (Reported </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Living with Minerals 4 in November 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">):</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 108pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2013-2014:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[in progress]: Future minerals supply (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Future minerals scenarios for the UK – looking 30+ years ahead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). (To be reported to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Living with Minerals 5 in November 2014</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 108pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Reports and recommendations from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Working Groups are sent as appropriate to Government Departments, or followed up in other ways as far as limited resources permit, including publishing material on Forum website hosted by the BGS and members’ websites (e.g. at CBI, MIRO and several min</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eral trade associations).</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 108pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Following the 2010-2011 cycle of work, discussions are in progress with the Institute of Quarrying on developing an economical and readily accessible distance learning module for local authority planners new to minerals work, to h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">elp get them up to speed quickly on the special features and legislative and procedural framework that applies to mineral planning  This is aimed at dealing with a perceived shortage of relevant expertise which causes avoidable delays in the preparation of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> minerals plans and decisions on applications for permissions.  Also arising from the 2011-2012 Working Group on improving the extractive industries’ communications with the wider public, which is so often initially hostile to proposals for onshore mineral</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> extraction, discussions are being held with the Earth Science Teachers Association and the Geological Society of whether some core material on UK-won minerals could be included in suitable parts of the revised secondary school syllabus.</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 67.02pt; padding-left:4.98pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Any stru</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ctured engagement of this type requires a certain amount of funding for secretariat services and meetings. In the case of UKMF this has been provided by the CBI Minerals Group.  Support is provided in the following ways:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Booking and paying for room hire fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r 3 plenary meetings a year;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Re-imbursement of a Secretary’s expenses in preparing for and minuting plenary meetings;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Re-imbursement of secretariat and research expenditure by Forum Working Groups where these cannot be met within participating organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Provision of a platform at the CBI’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Living with Minerals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Conferences for reports on the findings of UKMF Working Groups.</span></li></ol><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Chairmanship, Secretariat and the input of personal time:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Partly as a matter of practicality, and also in order to endure the neutr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ality of the Forum within the context of financial sponsorship by the extractive industries acting collectively, the Forum has so far been chaired by retired officials from DCLG and Natural England, serving broadly 3 year terms.  Secretaries have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">foun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d from retired officers of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mineral trade associations and local government.  In view of the inevitable pressures of the daytime jobs of Forum members, it has drawn heavily on people retired from its constituent organisations to help run meetings and do the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> heavy lifting required in preparing and following-up Working Group reports.</span></li></ol><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Discussion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: UKMF as an example of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs:  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This issue can be considered in two parts; fi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rst</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the contribution of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMF to governance and business in the UK, and second, whether it offers a model for UK-based or owned mineral extraction companies operating internationally.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UKMF is entirely focussed on the relationship between the extractive industries operating in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK and central and local government, statutory regulators and the voluntary environmental NGOs.  A key advantage in its approach to issues of common interest and concern is its culture.  It works as a round-table, is non-adversarial and inclusive, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is founded on mutual respect for members’ differing objectives and points of view.  This is of particular benefit in view of the potential for conflicts between the need for minerals by society and the economy and the possibility of adverse impacts of mine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ral working on habitats, landscape, heritage and hydrology, which, where present, need to be contained by mitigating measures to an acceptable level.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What makes this mode of dialogue possible is a set of shared values and common assumptions about governanc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e and civic society in the UK; the rule of law, a high standard of competence and probity in the public services and a generally consultative culture in the preparation of legislation and its application by the statutory regulators, backed up by impartial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oversight by the courts.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">After 6 years the UKMF is still evolving, and its continuation is of course highly dependent on the interest, support and motivation of its membership, very largely provided </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">pro bono</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in addition to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">members’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regular work and activit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at the level of national policy making and strategic analysis of the present and future state of mineral extraction in the UK, it has since 2007 provided an arena that is not otherwise available, and as such it must be considered as a best p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ractice example in response to the question identified in 1. above.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whether its model could be adopted by UK-based mineral extractors in their relations with governments, regulators and NGO in respect of their overseas operations is not for UKMF to say.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the core principles of round-table non-adversarial discu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssion in a climate of mutual respect to work it would need the same acceptance by all the parties of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the factors on which UKMF relies in the UK: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good state governance, peaceful society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, probity in industry - government relations, NGOs with an understanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and basic acceptance of the economic drivers of mineral extraction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and respect for the rule of law.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.75pt; margin:0pt 0pt 16.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>